Unstructed Stochasticity

Module 1: Unstructured Population Models

Section 3: Population dynamics and stochasticity

Deterministic vs. stochastic factors

  • Deterministic factors are predictable, such as predation, competition, etc.
  • Stochastic factors are unpredictable

Basic forms of stochasticity and definitions

Demographic stochasticity

Demographic stochasticity refers to chance events of individual mortality and reproduction (inevitable deviation in mean birth and death rates) (Lande et al., 2003).

  • Only significant in small populations
  • Example 1: Flipping a coin 10,000 times, one will get approximately 5,000 times heads; flipping the same coin 100 times, there could be some deviations from the expected 50:50; flipping the same coin 10 times, it is not suprising that one only gets 2 heads. The probability of getting head is approaching 0.5 as the number of trials increases.
# toss a coin
toss10 <- sample(c(0,1), size = 10, prob = c(0.5,0.5), replace = TRUE)
toss100 <- sample(c(0,1), size = 100, prob = c(0.5,0.5), replace = TRUE)
toss10k <- sample(c(0,1), size = 10000, prob = c(0.5,0.5), replace = TRUE)
results <- data.frame(c(sum(toss10), 10-sum(toss10)),
                      c(sum(toss100), 100-sum(toss100)),
                      c(sum(toss10k), 10000-sum(toss10k)))
colnames(results) <- c("10 tosses", "100 tosses", "10,000 tosses")
rownames(results) <- c("heads", "tails")
results
##       10 tosses 100 tosses 10,000 tosses
## heads         7         52          5051
## tails         3         48          4949
  • Example 2: The expected sex ratio for a newborn is 50:50. When there 3 new births, we cannot have 50% males and 50% females. Unbalanced sex ratio will influence future birth rate, especially in a small population. Similarly, a death rate of 0.2 does not mean after a year an animal is 0.8 aliveit either survives or dies. When the population size is large, we may use the product of the total populatiom and a mean birth/death rate to estimate the number of births/deaths. However, such estimation is not accurate when the population size is small.

Environmental stochasticity

Environmental stochasticity often refers to temporal fluctuations in the probability of mortality and reproduction (unpredictable catastrophes) (Lande et al., 2003)

  • Often driven directly or indirectly by weather
  • Example: Climate factors have a strong influence on the ecology of red deer on Rum (Albon et al., 1987). Real-world data between 1971 and 1991 has shown that the changes in red deer population size correlates strongly with annual rainfall (Benton et al., 1995).
Red deer (Cervus elaphus) young stage (Wikimedia Commons, credit: Charles J. Sharp)

Sampling error

Sampling error (or sampling variance) is the measurement error in estimates of population size or density. Some researchers categorized it as a basic form of stochasticity (Lande et al., 2003), while some distinguished it from deterministic and stochastic factors (Mills, 2007).

Implications of variation in population growth

  • An obvious outcome is that future population size outcomes become more uncertain and more variable.
  • A less intuitive outcome is that the likelihood of any particular population size at time tt in the future becomes more skewed (most populations being relatively small, with a tiny fraction being huge). We will discuss it soon.

Stochastic effects to population growth rates

Arithmetic mean vs. geometric mean

  • Let AA and GG denote the arithmetic and geometric mean, respectively,
    A=1ki=1ki,A=1ki=1ki,
    G=(i=1ki)1k.G=(i=1ki)1k.
  • Example: Consider Nt=tNt1Nt=tNt1, where NtNt is the population at time tt, and during each time interval (t1,t)(t1,t) the growth rate is tt. Assume t=1.55t=1.55 or t=0.55t=0.55 with the same probability. Assuming that the population grows at a constant arithmetic mean rate A=(1.55+0.55)/2=1.05A=(1.55+0.55)/2=1.05, the population at t=16t=16 is
    N16=1.0516N0=2.18N0.N16=1.0516N0=2.18N0.
     Instead, if we assume that the growth rate alternated between 1.551.55 and 0.550.55, the population at t=16t=16 becomes
    N16=1.5580.558N0=[(1.550.55)1/2]16N0=0.28N0,N16=1.5580.558N0=[(1.550.55)1/2]16N0=0.28N0,
     which indicates that the variation in population growth leads to a likely decline for the population, even though the (arithmetic) average growth rate is larger than 1 (Mills, 2007). Here, the geometric mean growth rate is G=(1.550.55)1/20.9233G=(1.550.55)1/20.9233.
N0 <- 1
lambda <- matrix(rbinom(1600, 1, 0.5), ncol = 16)
lambda[lambda==1] <- 1.55
lambda[lambda==0] <- 0.55
# lambda is a 100-by-16 matrix
# each row represents a possible population change in 16 years
outcome <- N0*apply(lambda, 1, prod)
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
boxplot(outcome, main = "Boxplot with outliers", 
        ylab = "Final population size")
boxplot(outcome, outline = FALSE, main = "Boxplot without outliers")

    ln(12k)=ln1+ln2++lnk=r1+r2++rk,ln(12k)=ln1+ln2++lnk=r1+r2++rk,
     which gives
    ln(12k)1/k=1kln(12k)=1k(r1+r2++rk),ln(12k)1/k=1kln(12k)=1k(r1+r2++rk),
     and thus
    lnG=rA.lnG=rA.
  • Variation around : Increasing the variance of the growth rates (22) makes the geometric mean growth rate less than the arithmetic mean. Let t=A+tt=A+t, where tt is the deviation of tt from the arithmetic mean AA with zero mean. Using Taylor expansion, one could obtain
    lnt =lnA+ln(1+t/A)=lnA+t/A(t/A)2/2+O(3t).lnt=lnA+ln(1+t/A) =lnA+t/A(t/A)2/2+O(t3).
     Hence, taking the expectation of both sides gives
    rA=E(lnt)lnAE[(tA)2]22A=lnA222A,rA=E(lnt)lnAE[(tA)2]2A2=lnA22A2,
     which further gives
    Gexp(lnA222A).Gexp(lnA22A2).
     In fact, the geometric mean is always no larger than the arithmetic mean (and they are equal if and only if every term is the same).

Temporal autocorrelation

  • Above examples assume that rtrt does not depend on previous growth rates, nor will it influence subsequent growth rates. The autocorrelation describes the relationship between rtrt and rt+rt+, its value at a time lag . One way to incorporate teporal autocorrelation is to:
    rt+=rA+(rtrA)+t+,rt+=rA+(rtrA)+t+,
     where is the coefficient of lag- autocorrelation, and tN(0,2)tN(0,2) is white noise with zero mean and constant variance. An example would be the case =1=1 (lag-1 autocorrelation), where rt+1=rA+(rtrA)+t+1rt+1=rA+(rtrA)+t+1. When =0=0, rt+1=rA+t+1rt+1=rA+t+1 and there is no temporal autocorrelation.

Estimating population growth rates

Process error

Process error results from variation in true population size due to biotic or abiotic processes (Ahrestani et al., 2013).

  • Environmental and demographic stochasticity are examples of process errors
  • When only process error exists, the population at each time tt, NtNt, is known and accurate. The growth rate tt is a random variable. For example, a geometric model with only process error can be described as
    Nt+1t=tNt,N(,2p),Nt+1=tNt,tN(,p2),
     where tt follows a normal distribution with mean and variance 2pp2.
  • Since the population at each time tt, NtNt, is known and accurate, we can calculate the estimated growth rate using geometric mean
     =(i=1tNiNi1)1t,^=(i=1tNiNi1)1t,
     or equivalently,
    r =1ti=1tlnNiNi1.r^=1ti=1tlnNiNi1.
  • We can see that the estimated growth rate is only related to the initial and the final population size, as all the terms between them can be cancelled out. In other words,
     =(NtN0)1t^=(NtN0)1t
     and
    r =lnNtlnN0t.r^=lnNtlnN0t.

Observation error

Observation error results from variation in the methodology used to obtain the population size (Ahrestani et al., 2013).

  • Examples of observation error include difficulty in counting animals, which might due to lack of technical expertise, insufficient funding, etc.
  • When only observation error exists, the growth rate is accurate. A possible geometric model with only observation error can be described as
    lnNtt=lnN0+rt+t,N(0,2o),lnNt=lnN0+rt+t,tN(0,o2),
     where tt follows a normal distribution with mean 0 and variance 2oo2. Here we ignore the subscript of rr as we assume the growth rate is some constant. We could also convert the above equation to
    Nt+1=tNtet,Nt+1=tNtet,
     where et>0et>0 so that the population is always non-negative.
  • The equation lnNt=lnN0+rt+tlnNt=lnN0+rt+t is in the form of a linear model in which lnNtlnNt is the response variable and tt is the predictor variable. Using simple linear regression, the slope of the fitted function is the estimated rr. Moreover, the yy-intercept is the estimated lnN0lnN0.
